snippet.textDisplay:
ok so stephen left danplan, and there's been a lot of comments saying "don't put the blame on daniel" saying he ha another side of the story, and honestly i can sort of understand why dan did what he did.

don't get me wrong, i don't think what he did was right, but to think he's some horrible person because of, potentially, the first big mistake we've heard of dan making isn't right either.

the main point of the issue was that dan called stephen nothing but "an employee", but that was when they had their "big argument", and we all know arguments tend to lead to high stress and emotions and people saying things they don't mean or regret later. and it's evident dan was facing a lot of stress; planning and editing and organising every video, trying to please viewers, (and if this was after going back to school) studies, and on top of all of that, the worry that stephen would be leaving.

the reason i don't believe he truly meant it was because he's really a nice guy. you could argue that he puts on a persona for youtube, which is entirely possible, but i doubt he regularly gets mad either. i mean the entire fandom was terrified when the jay and fruit incident happened, jay himself seemed pretty scared too, so it's unlikely anyone expected him to be serious/angry, which basically kinda proves that he doesn't do this very often. in fact, the video where hosuh and elias where making food kinda shows how even after a whole day of work he comes back tired but still jokes and has fun. he had a nosebleed man like what

stephen leaving would have been disastrous (as it is now but now there's the complication of this dan vs stephen thing), potentially ending the career, the work that dan and hosuh AND stephen and everyone else had put in for 4-5 years, something dan has already committed himself to, while stephen has not. it's likely that the money danplan made was being split into several different places; paying the animators, paying for the production of merch, maybe even charity. maybe it was hard to give stephen a higher pay, or maybe the fact that stephen asked for a higher pay itself dissuaded dan from doing so (they're both really full of pride hosuhs had to put aside his pride to get them to reconcile even in april fools vids)

with all this stress plus added emotions from arguing itself, it's easy for him, or anyone really, to say what he did.

dan making more money from this than stephen makes sense, stephen himself said so, but it's true that stephen deserves a bigger cut/ more credit than he's getting. i'm sure dan sees this too. im thinking the argument likely put their relationship in a really awkward state, and considering they have to work together this isn't really ideal. it's likely the reason why dan replied stephens "how many views did i contribute" question with "i can't tell you" (other than the fact that it's actually hard to tell i mean it's not like every view has a 'i came here for steven' pinned next to it but i know it's more of the meaning than the actual number) is probably because he wanted to avoid another fight, or just the general threat that stephen was going to leave. (and yet again, pride)

this is all speculation, i don't know if any of this is true. what dan did wasn't right, but he's not entirely to blame. stephen definitely needs to be treated with more respect and given more credit, but so does dan. sure he doesn't seem to contribute much to the friendly banter in the videos, but his role is to be the leader, the planner. he has to come up with the ideas, script things, and when the gang goes off on tangent, bring them back or improvise something entirely new. he spends hours working on every video we watch, every video they record. he got a NOSEBLEED for whatever's sake, y'all be sleeping on this man. jokes aside, it's hard being a leader, making decisions for a group or not complying to everyone's needs. it's not easy to do the right things or say the right things at any if not every given time

so give him time to tell his side of the story, whether y'all stan him or not. he's not just a human being, but THE human being whose hard work had given us five glorious years of danplan, brought us the stephen we all know and love and have gotten live changing advice from, and who has reasons behind what he did, right or wrong.

let him share his story y'all.
